":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Morville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Moorfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moorfield","meanings":["English: locative name from Morville (Shrops), which is recorded as  <i>Mamerfeld</i> in the 12th century,  <i>Momerefeld</i> in 1255, and  <i>Morfelde</i> in 1464."]}]},{"name":"Eudes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Eade  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Eads","meanings":["and Norwegian equivalent of <b>Matthew</b> ."]},{"name":"Eade","meanings":["Respelling of   Cade ."]},{"name":"Edes","meanings":["This name is found as a variant or pet form of   Edith   in Yorkshire from the 15th century onwards. It is recorded as a baptismal name in the 16th century. In present-day use it probably refers to the biblical ‘Garden of Eden’, crew ῾<i>eden</i> ‘place of pleasure’. As a boy's name it may also represent a variant of   Aidan   or a transferred use of a surname, itself derived in the Middle Ages from a given name <i>Edun</i> or <i>Edon</i>. This is of Old English origin, from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>hūn</i> ‘bear cub’."]},{"name":"Edds","meanings":["P